                  <p align="left"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br>
                    From the twelfth century until the beginning of the twentieth 
                    century, Ireland was increasingly governed by <a href="Law_intro_scope.htm" >English 
                    common law</a> and in 1800 it became fully integrated into 
                    the United Kingdom by the Act of Union passed in that year. 
                    <br>
                    <br>
                    Independence from the UK for 26 of the 32 counties was achieved 
                    in 1922 which became the &#145;Irish Free State&#146; (renamed 
                    &#145;Ireland&#146; in 1937) with its own Constitution. Six 
                    counties in Northern Ireland remained part of the United Kingdom.</font><br>
                  </p>
                  <p align="left"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">The 
                    1922 &amp; 1937 Constitutions carried all previous UK law 
                    forward into Irish law, and certain pre-1922 UK statutes are 
                    still in force in Ireland, for example the Public Health (Ireland) 
                    Act, 1878.<br>
                    <br>
                    This Constitution established four main institutions &#150; 
                    the President (Uachtar&aacute;n na h&Eacute;ireann), the Oireachtas 
                    (Parliament), the Government and the Courts.<br>
                    <br>
                    The President is the directly-elected Head of State but his/her 
                    powers are largely ceremonial. The Oireachtas (Parliament) 
                    consists of two Houses &#150; the directly-elected D&aacute;il 
                    and indirectly-elected Seanad. The Government is the Executive 
                    and consists of the Taoiseach (Prime Minister) and Ministers.<br>
                    <br>
                    The Constitution contains a set of fundamental rights, e.g. 
                    rights to equality before the law, freedom of expression, 
                    freedom of religion, education, etc. The courts may issue 
                    binding decisions that legislation is unconstitutional if 
                    it breaches these fundamental rights.</font></p>
                  <p><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">The 
                    Constitution has been amended on numerous occasions, and each 
                    amendment requires a referendum. In 1972 the Constitution 
                    was amended to recognise Ireland&#146;s membership of the 
                    EEC (now the <a href="Law_intro_EU.htm" >EU 
                    or EC</a> ) and there have been similar amendments to recognise 
                    major new European Treaties.<br>
                    <br>
                    <a href="Law_intro_EU.htm" ><b>European Community 
                    Law</b></a> is binding on Ireland.<br>
                    <br>
                    </font><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Primary 
                    legislation in the form of <b>Acts</b> is created by the Parliament 
                    and subsequent secondary legislation (generally called <b>Statutory 
                    Instruments</b>) is made by Government Ministers (or possibly 
                    others) in accordance with the authority provided by the Act.<br>
                    <br>
                    Under the European Communities Act, a general enabling Act, 
                    certain European legislation is enacted directly into Irish 
                    law by Government Ministers using secondary legislation. In 
                    these cases the European legislation is effectively the &quot;primary&quot; 
                    legislation and is treated as such for the purposes of enviroLAW.<br>
                    <br>
                    In the case of litigation, all primary and secondary legislation 
                    is interpreted by the Courts with reference to <a href="Law_intro_scope.htm" >Case 
                    Law</a>.</font><br>
                  </p>
